<p><b>Roman Osipovich Jakobson</b>, (Russian, <b>Роман Осипович Якобсон</b>), (11 October 1896 – 18 July 1982) was a <a href="/wiki/Russia" title="Russia">Russian</a> linguist and literary critic, associated with the <a href="/wiki/Russian_Formalism" title="Russian Formalism" class="mw-redirect">Formalist</a> school. He became one of the most influential <a href="/wiki/Linguistics" title="Linguistics">linguists</a> of the 20th century by pioneering the development of <a href="/wiki/Structuralism" title="Structuralism">structural analysis</a> of <a href="/wiki/Language" title="Language">language</a>, <a href="/wiki/Poetry" title="Poetry">poetry</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Art" title="Art">art</a>.</p>
